ition of the New Testament\n|location = New York\n|publisher = Oxford University Press\n|year = 2000\n|url = https://books.google.ca/books?id=kLDyPGJldl8C&printsec=frontcover\n|isbn = 978-0-195-11240-5\n|doi = 10.1093/acprof:oso/9780195112405.001.0001\n|oclc = 827708997\n|ref = harv\n}}\n* {{cite journal\n|last = Vasileiadis\n|first = Pavlos D.\n|title = The pronunciation of the sacred Tetragrammaton: An overview of a nomen revelatus that became a nomen absconditus\n|journal = [[Judaica Ukrainica]]\n|publisher = [[National University of Kyiv-Mohyla Academy]]\n|volume = 2\n|year = 2013\n|url = http://judaicaukrainica.ukma.edu.ua/ckfinder/userfiles/files/JU_2_2013_Vasileiadis.pdf\n|ref = harv\n}}\n* {{cite journal\n|title = Aspects of rendering the sacred Tetragrammaton in Greek\n|first = Pavlos D.\n|last = Vasileiadis\n|journal = [[Open Theology]]\n|volume = 1\n|issue = 1\n|year = 2014\n|pages = 56\u201388\n|url = https://www.academia.edu/10457621\n|location = Berlin, Germany\n|publisher = De Gruyter\n|oclc = 927128789\n|issn = 2300-6579\n|doi = 10.2478/opth-2014-0006\n|ref = harv\n}}\n* {{cite journal\n|last=Vasileiadis\n|first=Pavlos D.\n|url=https://www.academia.edu/30967321\n|title=The god Iao and his connection with the Biblical God, with special emphasis on the manuscript 4QpapLXXLevb (\"\u039f \u03b8\u03b5\u03cc\u03c2 \u0399\u03b1\u03ce \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03b7 \u03c3\u03c7\u03ad\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03bc\u03b5 \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u0392\u03b9\u03b2\u03bb\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u0398\u03b5\u03cc, \u03bc\u03b5 \u03b9\u03b4\u03b9\u03b1\u03af\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1\u03b7 \u03b5\u03c3\u03c4\u03af\u03b1\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf \u03c7\u03b5\u03b9\u03c1\u03cc\u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03c6\u03bf 4QpapLXXLevb\")\n|journal=Vetus Testamentum et Hellas\n|volume=4\n|date = 2017\n|pp=48\u201351\n|issn=2459-2552\n|oclc=1085412017\n|location=Aristotle University of Thessaloniki, Greece\n|publisher=School of Pastoral and Social Theology\n|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book\n|last = Vasileiadis\n|first = Pavlos D.\n|year = 2018\n|title = \"Jesus, the New Testament, and the sacred Tetragrammaton\" (\"\u039f \u0399\u03b7\u03c3\u03bf\u03cd\u03c2, \u03b7 \u039a\u03b1\u03b9\u03bd\u03ae \u0394\u03b9\u03b1\u03b8\u03ae\u03ba\u03b7 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03c4\u03bf \u03b9\u03b5\u03c1\u03cc \u03a4\u03b5\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1\u03b3\u03c1\u03ac\u03bc\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03bf\")\n|url = https://www.academia.edu/38647628\n|ref = harv\n}}\n* {{cite journal\n|last1=Vasileiadis\n|first1=Pavlos D.|last2=Gordon|first2=Nehemia|url=https://www.academia.edu/38634875\n|title=Transmission of the Tetragrammaton in Judeo-Greek and Christian Sources (\"\u0397 \u039c\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03b2\u03af\u03b2\u03b1\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a4\u03b5\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1\u03b3\u03c1\u03ac\u03bc\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03c2 \u0399\u03bf\u03c5\u03b4\u03b1\u03b9\u03bf-\u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ad\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03a7\u03c1\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03b1\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ad\u03c2 \u03a0\u03b7\u03b3\u03ad\u03c2\")|journal=Accademia: Revue de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Marsile Ficin|volume=18\n|year=2019|issn=1296-7645|oclc=43343733|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book\n|last = Wagner\n|first = J. Ross\n|author-link = \n|title = Heralds of the Good News: Isaiah and Paul in Concert in the Letter to the Romans\n|publisher = BRILL\n|year = 2003\n|url = https://books.google.com.gt/books?id=qoJd-73kClgC\n|isbn = 978-0-391-04204-9\n|ref = harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n|last = Wilkinson\n|first = Robert J.\n|title = Tetragrammaton: Western Christians and the Hebrew Name of God: From the Beginnings to the Seventeenth Century.\n|series = Studies in the History of Christian Traditions\n|volume = Vol. 179\n|date = 4 February 2015\n|location = Leiden\n|publisher = Brill\n|isbn = 978-90-04-28817-1\n|doi = 10.1163/9789004288171\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1xyoBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA93\n|ref = harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n|last = Wright\n|first = Nicholas Thomas \n|title = The New Testament and the People of God\n|publisher = Fortress Press\n|year = 1992\n|isbn = 0800626818\n|ref = harv\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.nestle-aland.com/en/read-na28-online/ Complete Greek text of the New Testament]\n* [http://www.studylight.org/isb/ Complete Greek text of the Septuagint hyperlinked to Strong's concordance]\n* [http://www.ecmarsh.com/lxx/ Brenton's English translation of the Septuagint]\n* [https://www.ellopos.net/elpenor/greek-texts/septuagint/default.asp Brenton's English translation and Greek text in parallel columns]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091027085452/http://www.geocities.com/r_grant_jones/Rick/Septuagint/splist1.htm Instances where the New Testament quotes the Septuagint against the Masoretic Hebrew]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091027085425/http://www.geocities.com/r_grant_jones/Rick/Septuagint/splistMT.htm Instances where the New Testament agrees with the Masoretic Hebrew meaning]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060305150637/http://www.exc.com/JoelHoffman/Excerpts/ITB-p95.pdf Some names in the Septuagint and the Masoretic Text]\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2011}}\n\n[[Category:Names of God]]\n[[Category:Beliefs and practices of Jehovah's Witnesses]]\n[[Category:Bible-related controversies]]\n[[Category:Tetragrammaton]]\n[[Category:Yahweh]]\n", "name_user": "Bealtainem\u00ed", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNomina sacra in the New Testament:inserted \"(\" where needed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Names_and_titles_of_God_in_the_New_Testament"}
{"title_page": "Nilave Mugam Kaattu", "text_new": "{{short description|1999 film by Kalanjiyam}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Nilave Mugam Kaattu\n| image          = Nilave Mugam Kattu DVD cover.jpg\n| caption        = DVD cover\n| director       = [[Kalanjiyam]]\n| producer       = S. Rajaram\n| writer         = Mu. Kalangiyam\n| story          = V. Umakanth\n| based on       = ''[[Anuraga Sangama]]'' (Kannada)\n| starring       = {{ubl|[[Karthik (actor)|Karthik]]|[[Ramki]]|[[Devayani (actress)|Devayani]]|[[Nizhalgal Ravi]]|[[Delhi Ganesh]]|[[Srividya]]|[[Sarath Babu]]|[[Manivannan]]|[[Vadivelu]]}}\n| music          = [[Ilaiyaraaja]]\n| cinematography = Abdul Rahman\n| editing        = [[V. T. Vijayan]]<br />[[B. Lenin]]\n| studio         = Mahalakshmi International\n| distributor    =\n| released       = {{Film date|df=y|1999|04|30}}\n| country        = India\n| runtime        = 160 minutes\n| language       = Tamil\n}}\n\n'''''Nilave Mugam Kaattu''''' ({{trans|Oh Moon, please show your face}}) is a 1999 Indian [[Tamil language|Tamil]]-language film directed by [[Kalanjiyam]] and starring [[Karthik (actor)|Karthik]], [[Ramki]] and [[Devayani (actress)|Devayani]]. The film, produced by S. Rajaram, has a musical score by [[Ilaiyaraaja]] and was released on 30 April 1999 to negative reviews.\n\nThe film is a remake of the Kannada film ''[[Anuraga Sangama]]'' (1995) starring [[Ramesh Aravind]], [[Kumar Govind]] and [[Sudharani]] which itself was inspired by [[Charlie Chaplin]]'s ''[[City Lights]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jointscene.com/movies/kollywood/Nilave_Mugam_Kaattu/6137|title=Find Tamil Movie Nilave Mugam Kaattu|accessdate=2011-12-06|publisher=jointscene.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://popcorn.oneindia.in/title/6510/nilavey-mugam-kaattu.html|title=Nilavey Mugam Kaattu|accessdate=2011-12-06|publisher=popcorn.oneindia.in}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cinesouth.com/cgi-bin/filmography/newfilmdb.cgi?name=nilave%20mugam%20kaattu|title=Filmography of nilave mugam kaattu|accessdate=2011-12-06|publisher=cinesouth.com}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n\nMurthy ([[Karthik (actor)|Karthik]]) and Prakash ([[Ramki]]) become best friends since Prakash's father ([[Nizhalgal Ravi]]) killed Murthy's mother in a car accident. Despite his father's refusal, Prakash takes Murthy into his house. But Prakash's parents do not like their son making friendship with Murthy who is poor and they consider it to be a status issue.\n\nA few years later, when Prakash goes to the US to study. Meanwhile, Prakash's parents scold Murthy with a plan to make him leave their house. Murthy feels bad and decides to leave Prakash's house without informing anyone. An old police constable accommodates Murthy who treats him like his late son Govind and the man begins to call him by that name. Murthy also comes under the identity of Govind now and starts working in an apartment by helping the residents of that apartment. Murthy has a percussion instrument and plays his favourite tune always. Murthy meets Kasturi ([[Devayani (actress)|Devayani]]) a [[Visual impairment|blind]] flower seller and falls in love with her. Kasturi also likes Murthy's character after he saved her from a few thugs who tried to molest her. Kasturi's father ([[Delhi Ganesh]]) is a drunkard and dies in an accident which leaves Kasturi alone with an [[eye injury]] which made her blind. Murthy takes care of Kasturi now and takes her to a doctor (Srividya) with an aim of getting her vision. The doctor advises Kasturi to undergo a surgery following which there are chances for getting her vision. In order to pay for the operation, Murthy takes some money from a drunk man's house. In a misunderstanding, he gets arrested by the police and is sent to jail.\n\nKasturi gets her vision after surgery but she is worried as Murthy has never returned. The doctor takes Kasturi to her home and asks her to stay until Murthy comes back. In the meantime, Prakash returns to India after completing his studies and he falls in love with Kasturi at first sight. Prakash convinces his parents to arrange his wedding with Kasturi. Although Kasturi is not interested in this proposal, she is convinced by the doctor as there is no point in worrying about Murthy who has disappeared for a while.\n\nKasturi, who cannot find Murthy, agrees to wed Prakash although she is not interested. Murthy is released by the police as he is proved innocent. One day, Prakash finds Murthy and is shocked to see his condition. Prakash takes Murthy along with him to his home. At Prakash's home, Murthy is shocked knowing that he is in love with Kasturi who has got her eyesight now. Murthy decides to hide his identity to Kasturi (as she knows him only by the name Govind and she has not seen him before). Murthy does not even speak in front of Kasturi as she will be able to identify his voice. Murthy also convinces the doctor to not reveal about him to Kasturi as he wanted his close friend Prakash to lead a happy life marrying Kasturi.\n\nOn the day of the wedding, a poor boy comes to the marriage hall looking for food. He plays Murthy's tune with the percussion instrument which shocks Kasturi. She rushes to the boy and enquires about Govind. The boy points out Murthy as the one who taught him to play this tune while he was begging before. Now Kasturi understands that Prakash's friend Murthy is none other than Govind whom she was searching.\n\nKasturi runs towards Murthy and requests him to marry her. Murthy is shocked and speechless. Prakash's parents speak ill about Murthy and Kasturi. Prakash comes to the spot and asks the truth to Murthy. Murthy tries to manage the situation and finally, when Prakash asks him to make a promise on him, Murthy does not do fearing any harm to Prakash. Murthy reveals the truth and wants Prakash to lead a joyful life which made him sacrifice his love.\n\nPrakash on hearing this is overwhelmed by the love of his friend and immediately asks him to marry Kasturi. Prakash promises to marry another girl for sure and requests Murthy not to hurt Kasturi. Murthy agrees and gets united with Kasturi.\n\n==Cast==\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Karthik (actor)|Karthik]] as Murthy / Govind\n* [[Ramki]] as Prakash\n* [[Devayani (actress)|Devayani]] as Kasthuri\n* [[Manivannan]]\n* [[Vadivelu]]\n* [[Sarath Babu]] as a police officer\n* [[Nizhalgal Ravi]] as Prakash's father\n* [[Srividya]] as a doctor\n* J. Lalitha as Prakash's mother\n* [[Delhi Ganesh]] as Kasthuri's father\n* Sundar\n* [[Chaplin Balu]]\n* Rajaputhran\n* Bayilvan Ranganathan\n* Anwar Ali Khan\n* Master Pradeep as Murthy (child)\n* [[Mahendran (actor)|Master Mahendran]] as Prakash (child)\n* [[Muthukaalai]]\n* [[Kalanjiyam]] in a cameo appearance\n{{colend}}\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Nilave Mugam Kaattu\n| type       = [[soundtrack]]\n| artist     = [[Ilaiyaraaja]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1999\n| recorded   = 1999\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Film soundtrack|Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length     = 31:21\n| label      =\n| producer   = [[Ilaiyaraaja]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\nThe film score and the soundtrack were composed by [[film composer]] [[Ilaiyaraaja]]. The soundtrack, released in 1999, features 6 tracks with lyrics written by Vasan, M. Mehta and Pazhani Bharathi. The soundtrack has received generally mixed reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.raaga.com/channels/tamil/moviedetail.asp?mid=t0000116|title=Nilavae Mugam Kaatu Songs|accessdate=2011-12-06|publisher=raaga.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hummaa.com/music/album/22164/Nilave+Mugam+Kaattu|title=Nilave Mugam Kaattu Songs|accessdate=2011-12-06|publisher=hummaa.com}}</ref><ref name=\"music review\">{{cite web |title=Nilavey Mugam Kaatu: Music Review |url=http://www.indolink.com/tamil/cinema/Music/Reviews/99/Nilavey_Mugam_Kaatu_202141.html|publisher=indolink.com |accessdate=2011-12-06}}</ref>\n\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n! Track !! Song !! Singer(s)!! Lyrics !! Duration\n|-\n|1 || \"Thendralai Kandu\" || [[Hariharan (singer)|Hariharan]], [[Ilaiyaraaja]] || rowspan=4|Vasan || 5:30\n|-\n|2 || \"Vaigai Nadhi Karai\" || Hariharan  ||  5:01\n|-\n|3 || \"Thanna Thaniyaka\" || Ilaiyaraaja || 5:03\n|-\n|4 || \"Suthatha Bhoomi\" || [[K. S. Chitra]] || 5:20\n|-\n|5 || \"Chittu Parakkuthu\" || [[Shankar Mahadevan]], [[Sujatha Mohan]] || M. Mehta || 5:03\n|-\n|6 || \"Poonkaaththu Adhu\" || [[S. P. Balasubrahmanyam]], Ilaiyaraaja || Pazhani Bharathi || 5:24\n|}\n\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = Indolink\n| rev1Score = Mixed<ref name=\"music review\" />\n}}\n\n==Reception==\n\nThe film received generally negative reviews. B. Balaji of ''Thenisai.com'' and Sandya Krishna of ''Indolink.com'' gave the film 1.5 out of 5.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenisai.com/tamil/movies-cinema/nilave-mugam-kaattu-tamil-movies.htm |title=Nilave Mugam Kaattu |accessdate=2011-12-06 |publisher=thenisai.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120909110827/http://www.thenisai.com/tamil/movies-cinema/nilave-mugam-kaattu-tamil-movies.htm |archivedate=9 September 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indolink.com/tamil/cinema/Reviews/articles/Nilavae_Mugam_Kaattu_162450.html|title=Nilavae Mugam Kaattu: Movie Review|accessdate=2011-12-06|publisher=indolink.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0292150}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|id=nilave-mugam-kattu|title=Nilave Mugam Kattu}}\n\n[[Category:1999 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Tamil remakes of Kannada films]]\n[[Category:Tamil film scores by Ilaiyaraaja]]\n[[Category:Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:1990s Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian romance films]]\n[[Category:1990s romance films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1999 film by Kalanjiyam}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Nilave Mugam Kaattu\n| image          = Nilave Mugam Kattu DVD cover.jpg\n| caption        = DVD cover\n| director       = [[Kalanjiyam]]\n| producer       = S. Rajaram\n| writer         = Mu. Kalangiyam\n| story          = V. Umakanth\n| based on       = ''[[Anuraga Sangama]]'' (Kannada)\n| starring       = {{ubl|[[Karthik (actor)|Karthik]]|[[Ramki]]|[[Devayani (actress)|Devayani]]|[[Nizhalgal Ravi]]|[[Delhi Ganesh]]|[[Srividya]]|[[Sarath Babu]]|[[Manivannan]]|[[Vadivelu]]}}\n| music          = [[Ilaiyaraaja]]\n| cinematography = Abdul Rahman\n| editing        = [[V. T. Vijayan]]<br />[[B. Lenin]]\n| studio         = Mahalakshmi International\n| distributor    =\n| released       = {{Film date|df=y|1999|04|30}}\n| country        = India\n| runtime        = 160 minutes\n| language       = Tamil\n}}\n\n'''''Nilave Mugam Kaattu''''' ({{trans|Oh Moon, please show your face}}) is a 1999 Indian [[Tamil language|Tamil]]-language film directed by [[Kalanjiyam]] and starring [[Karthik (actor)|Karthik]], [[Ramki]] and [[Devayani (actress)|Devayani]]. The film, produced by S. Rajaram, has a musical score by [[Ilaiyaraaja]] and was released on 30 April 1999 to negative reviews.\n\nThe film is a remake of the Kannada film ''[[Anuraga Sangama]]'' (1995) starring [[Ramesh Aravind]], [[Kumar Govind]] and [[Sudharani]] which itself was inspired by [[Charlie Chaplin]]'s ''[[City Lights]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jointscene.com/movies/kollywood/Nilave_Mugam_Kaattu/6137|title=Find Tamil Movie Nilave Mugam Kaattu|accessdate=2011-12-06|publisher=jointscene.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://popcorn.oneindia.in/title/6510/nilavey-mugam-kaattu.html|title=Nilavey Mugam Kaattu|accessdate=2011-12-06|publisher=popcorn.oneindia.in}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cinesouth.com/cgi-bin/filmography/newfilmdb.cgi?name=nilave%20mugam%20kaattu|title=Filmography of nilave mugam kaattu|accessdate=2011-12-06|publisher=cinesouth.com}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n\nMurthy ([[Karthik (actor)|Karthik]]) and Prakash ([[Ramki]]) become best friends since Prakash's father ([[Nizhalgal Ravi]]) killed Murthy's mother in a car accident. Despite his father's refusal, Prakash takes Murthy into his house. But Prakash's parents do not like their son making friendship with Murthy who is poor and they consider it to be a status issue.\n\nA few years later, when Prakash goes to the US to study. Meanwhile, Prakash's parents scold Murthy with a plan to make him leave their house. Murthy feels bad and decides to leave Prakash's house without informing anyone. An old police constable accommodates Murthy who treats him like his late son Govind and the man begins to call him by that name. Murthy also comes under the identity of Govind now and starts working in an apartment by helping the residents of that apartment. Murthy has a percussion instrument and plays his favourite tune always. Murthy meets Kasturi ([[Devayani (actress)|Devayani]]) a [[Visual impairment|blind]] flower seller and falls in love with her. Kasturi also likes Murthy's character after he saved her from a few thugs who tried to molest her. Kasturi's father ([[Delhi Ganesh]]) is a drunkard and dies in an accident which leaves Kasturi alone with an [[eye injury]] which made her blind. Murthy takes care of Kasturi now and takes her to a doctor (Srividya) with an aim of getting her vision. The doctor advises Kasturi to undergo a surgery following which there are chances for getting her vision. In order to pay for the operation, Murthy takes some money from a drunk man's house. In a misunderstanding, he gets arrested by the police and is sent to jail.\n\nKasturi gets her vision after surgery but she is worried as Murthy has never returned. The doctor takes Kasturi to her home and asks her to stay until Murthy comes back. In the meantime, Prakash returns to India after completing his studies and he falls in love with Kasturi at first sight. Prakash convinces his parents to arrange his wedding with Kasturi. Although Kasturi is not interested in this proposal, she is convinced by the doctor as there is no point in worrying about Murthy who has disappeared for a while.\n\nKasturi, who cannot find Murthy, agrees to wed Prakash although she is not interested. Murthy is released by the police as he is proved innocent. One day, Prakash finds Murthy and is shocked to see his condition. Prakash takes Murthy along with him to his home. At Prakash's home, Murthy is shocked knowing that he is in love with Kasturi who has got her eyesight now. Murthy decides to hide his identity to Kasturi (as she knows him only by the name Govind and she has not seen him before). Murthy does not even speak in front of Kasturi as she will be able to identify his voice. Murthy also convinces the doctor to not reveal about him to Kasturi as he wanted his close friend Prakash to lead a happy life marrying Kasturi.\n\nOn the day of the wedding, a poor boy comes to the marriage hall looking for food. He plays Murthy's tune with the percussion instrument which shocks Kasturi. She rushes to the boy and enquires about Govind. The boy points out Murthy as the one who taught him to play this tune while he was begging before. Now Kasturi understands that Prakash's friend Murthy is none other than Govind whom she was searching.\n\nKasturi runs towards Murthy and requests him to marry her. Murthy is shocked and speechless. Prakash's parents speak ill about Murthy and Kasturi. Prakash comes to the spot and asks the truth to Murthy. Murthy tries to manage the situation and finally, when Prakash asks him to make a promise on him, Murthy does not do fearing any harm to Prakash. Murthy reveals the truth and wants Prakash to lead a joyful life which made him sacrifice his love.\n\nPrakash on hearing this is overwhelmed by the love of his friend and immediately asks him to marry Kasturi. Prakash promises that he will get married to some other girl for sure and requests Murthy not to hurt Kasturi. Murthy agrees and gets united with Kasturi.\n\n==Cast==\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Karthik (actor)|Karthik]] as Murthy / Govind\n* [[Ramki]] as Prakash\n* [[Devayani (actress)|Devayani]] as Kasthuri\n* [[Manivannan]]\n* [[Vadivelu]]\n* [[Sarath Babu]] as a police officer\n* [[Nizhalgal Ravi]] as Prakash's father\n* [[Srividya]] as a doctor\n* J. Lalitha as Prakash's mother\n* [[Delhi Ganesh]] as Kasthuri's father\n* Sundar\n* [[Chaplin Balu]]\n* Rajaputhran\n* Bayilvan Ranganathan\n* Anwar Ali Khan\n* Master Pradeep as Murthy (child)\n* [[Mahendran (actor)|Master Mahendran]] as Prakash (child)\n* [[Muthukaalai]]\n* [[Kalanjiyam]] in a cameo appearance\n{{colend}}\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Nilave Mugam Kaattu\n| type       = [[soundtrack]]\n| artist     = [[Ilaiyaraaja]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1999\n| recorded   = 1999\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Film soundtrack|Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length     = 31:21\n| label      =\n| producer   = [[Ilaiyaraaja]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\nThe film score and the soundtrack were composed by [[film composer]] [[Ilaiyaraaja]]. The soundtrack, released in 1999, features 6 tracks with lyrics written by Vasan, M. Mehta and Pazhani Bharathi. The soundtrack has received generally mixed reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.raaga.com/channels/tamil/moviedetail.asp?mid=t0000116|title=Nilavae Mugam Kaatu Songs|accessdate=2011-12-06|publisher=raaga.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hummaa.com/music/album/22164/Nilave+Mugam+Kaattu|title=Nilave Mugam Kaattu Songs|accessdate=2011-12-06|publisher=hummaa.com}}</ref><ref name=\"music review\">{{cite web |title=Nilavey Mugam Kaatu: Music Review |url=http://www.indolink.com/tamil/cinema/Music/Reviews/99/Nilavey_Mugam_Kaatu_202141.html|publisher=indolink.com |accessdate=2011-12-06}}</ref>\n\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n! Track !! Song !! Singer(s)!! Lyrics !! Duration\n|-\n|1 || \"Thendralai Kandu\" || [[Hariharan (singer)|Hariharan]], [[Ilaiyaraaja]] || rowspan=4|Vasan || 5:30\n|-\n|2 || \"Vaigai Nadhi Karai\" || Hariharan  ||  5:01\n|-\n|3 || \"Thanna Thaniyaka\" || Ilaiyaraaja || 5:03\n|-\n|4 || \"Suthatha Bhoomi\" || [[K. S. Chitra]] || 5:20\n|-\n|5 || \"Chittu Parakkuthu\" || [[Shankar Mahadevan]], [[Sujatha Mohan]] || M. Mehta || 5:03\n|-\n|6 || \"Poonkaaththu Adhu\" || [[S. P. Balasubrahmanyam]], Ilaiyaraaja || Pazhani Bharathi || 5:24\n|}\n\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = Indolink\n| rev1Score = Mixed<ref name=\"music review\" />\n}}\n\n==Reception==\n\nThe film received generally negative reviews. B. Balaji of ''Thenisai.com'' and Sandya Krishna of ''Indolink.com'' gave the film 1.5 out of 5.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenisai.com/tamil/movies-cinema/nilave-mugam-kaattu-tamil-movies.htm |title=Nilave Mugam Kaattu |accessdate=2011-12-06 |publisher=thenisai.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120909110827/http://www.thenisai.com/tamil/movies-cinema/nilave-mugam-kaattu-tamil-movies.htm |archivedate=9 September 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indolink.com/tamil/cinema/Reviews/articles/Nilavae_Mugam_Kaattu_162450.html|title=Nilavae Mugam Kaattu: Movie Review|accessdate=2011-12-06|publisher=indolink.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0292150}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|id=nilave-mugam-kattu|title=Nilave Mugam Kattu}}\n\n[[Category:1999 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Tamil remakes of Kannada films]]\n[[Category:Tamil 