{"title_page": "1902 Calgary municipal election", "text_new": "{{Infobox election\n| election_name     = 1902 Calgary municipal election\n| country           = Calgary\n| type              = Municipal\n| ongoing           = no\n| previous_election = 1901 Calgary municipal election\n| previous_year     = 1901\n| next_election     = 1903 Calgary municipal election\n| next_year         = 1903\n| election_date     = {{start date|1902|12|08}}\n| image1            = [[file:Thos Underwood.jpg|150x150px]]\n| color1            = \n| candidate1        = [[Thomas Underwood]]\n| popular_vote1     = 419\n| percentage1       = 60.81%\n| image2            = <div style=\"width:150px;\"><span style=\"line-height:150px; vertical-align:center; text-align:center; color:{{Canadian party colour|AB|Independent Movement}}; font-size:38px;\"> '''W. P.'''</span></div>\n| color2            = \n| candidate2        = [[William Mahon Parslow]]\n| popular_vote2     = 270\n| percentage2       = 39.19%\n| image3            = \n| candidate3        = \n| color3            = \n| popular_vote3     = \n| percentage3       = \n| map_image         = \n| map_size          = 350px\n| map_caption       = \n| title             = Mayor\n| before_election   = [[Thomas Underwood]]\n| before_party      = \n| after_election    = [[Thomas Underwood]]\n| after_party       = \n}}\n\nThe '''1902 [[Calgary]] municipal election''' took place on December 8, 1902 to elect a [[List of mayors of Calgary|Mayor]] and nine Aldermen to sit on the nineteenth [[Calgary City Council]] from January 5, 1903 to January 5, 1904.<ref name=\"CGYHLDDec09Pg04\">{{cite news |title=Mayor Aldermen and School Trustees Elected. |url=http://contentdm.ucalgary.ca/digital/collection/p22007coll2/id/101386 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=The Daily Herald |issue=5551 |date=December 9, 1902 |location=Calgary, Canada |page=4}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe position for Mayor was contested by incumbent one-term mayor [[Thomas Underwood]], who also previously served seven terms as Alderman, and five-term Alderman [[William Mahon Parslow]].\n\nThe election was held under [[multiple non-transferable vote]] where each elector was able to cast a ballot for the mayor and up to three ballots for separate councillors with a voter's designated ward.\n\nKey issues in the election were expansion of the sewer system, public health related to the spread of scarlet fever, municipally owned electric light systems, prohibition, and expanded fire protection.<ref name=\"CGYHLDDec08Pg04\">{{cite news |title=Parish Politics Talked |url=http://contentdm.ucalgary.ca/digital/collection/p22007coll2/id/101377 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=The Daily Herald |issue=5550 |date=December 8, 1902 |location=Calgary, Canada |page=4}}</ref>\n\n==Results==\n===Mayor===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Candidate\n! Votes\n! Percent\n|-\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | [[Thomas Underwood]]\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | 419\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | 60.81%\n|-\n| [[William Mahon Parslow]]\n| style=\"text-align: right; \"| 270\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 39.19%\n|-\n! Total\n! style=\"text-align: right; \"|419\n! style=\"text-align: right; \"|-\n|}\n\n===Councillors===\n====Ward 1====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Candidate\n! Votes\n! Percent\n|-\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | [[John Emerson (mayor)|John Emerson]]\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | 183\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | \n|-\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | [[Silas Alexander Ramsay]]\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | 182\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | \n|-\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | [[Owen Herbert Bott]]\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | 174\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | \n|-\n| Mackenzie\n| style=\"text-align: right; \" | 154\n| style=\"text-align: right; \" | \n|-\n| Pitman\n| style=\"text-align: right; \" | 85\n| style=\"text-align: right; \" | \n|}\n\n====Ward 2====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Candidate\n! Votes\n! Percent\n|-\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | [[John Irwin (politician)|John Irwin]]\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | 185\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | \n|-\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | [[William Carson (Alberta politician)|William Carson]]\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | 143\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | \n|-\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | [[William John Binning]]\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | 95\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | \n|-\n| [[John Hamilton Kerr]]\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 80\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | \n|-\n| Brown\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 61\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | \n|}\n\n====Ward 3====\n*[[William Charles Gordon Armstrong]] - Acclaimed\n*[[Richard Addison Brocklebank]] - Acclaimed\n*[[James Abel Hornby]] - Acclaimed\n===School Trustees===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Candidate\n! Votes\n! Percent\n|-\n| R. F. Hutchings\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 408\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | \n|-\n| A. L. Cameron\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 364\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | \n|-\n| Clifford Jones\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 333\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | \n|-\n|}\n\n==September 1902 by-election==\nFollowing [[William Carson (Alberta politician)|William Carson's]] decision to decline the office of Alderman for Ward 2 communicated to the City Clerk on December 18, 1902, a by-election was held which was won by [[William Henry Cushing]].\n\n==Also See==\n*[[List of Calgary municipal elections]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|1}}\n\n==Sources==\n*Frederick Hunter: [http://freepages.rootsweb.com/~database/history/THE%20MAYORS%20AND%20COUNCILS%20OF%20THE%20CORPORATION%20OF%20CALGARY.htm THE MAYORS AND COUNCILS  OF  THE CORPORATION OF CALGARY] [https://web.archive.org/web/20200303003535/http://freepages.rootsweb.com/~database/history/THE%20MAYORS%20AND%20COUNCILS%20OF%20THE%20CORPORATION%20OF%20CALGARY.htm Archived March 3, 2020]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Calgary Municipal Election, 1902}}\n[[Category:Politics of Calgary]]\n[[Category:Municipal elections in Calgary]]\n[[Category:1902 elections in Canada]]\n[[Category:1900s in Calgary]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox election\n| election_name     = 1902 Calgary municipal election\n| country           = Calgary\n| type              = Municipal\n| ongoing           = no\n| previous_election = 1901 Calgary municipal election\n| previous_year     = 1901\n| next_election     = 1903 Calgary municipal election\n| next_year         = 1903\n| election_date     = {{start date|1902|12|08}}\n| image1            = [[file:Thos Underwood.jpg|150x150px]]\n| color1            = \n| candidate1        = [[Thomas Underwood]]\n| popular_vote1     = 419\n| percentage1       = 60.81%\n| image2            = <div style=\"width:150px;\"><span style=\"line-height:150px; vertical-align:center; text-align:center; color:{{Canadian party colour|AB|Independent Movement}}; font-size:38px;\"> '''W. P.'''</span></div>\n| color2            = \n| candidate2        = [[William Mahon Parslow]]\n| popular_vote2     = 270\n| percentage2       = 39.19%\n| image3            = \n| candidate3        = \n| color3            = \n| popular_vote3     = \n| percentage3       = \n| map_image         = \n| map_size          = 350px\n| map_caption       = \n| title             = Mayor\n| before_election   = [[Thomas Underwood]]\n| before_party      = \n| after_election    = [[Thomas Underwood]]\n| after_party       = \n}}\n\nThe '''1902 [[Calgary]] municipal election''' took place on December 8, 1902 to elect a [[List of mayors of Calgary|Mayor]] and nine Aldermen to sit on the nineteenth [[Calgary City Council]] from January 5, 1903 to January 5, 1904.<ref name=\"CGYHLDDec09Pg04\">{{cite news |title=Mayor Aldermen and School Trustees Elected. |url=http://contentdm.ucalgary.ca/digital/collection/p22007coll2/id/101386 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=The Daily Herald |issue=5551 |date=December 9, 1902 |location=Calgary, Canada |page=4}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe position for Mayor was contested by incumbent one-term mayor [[Thomas Underwood]], who also previously served seven terms as Alderman, and five-term Alderman [[William Mahon Parslow]].\n\nThe election was held under [[multiple non-transferable vote]] where each elector was able to cast a ballot for the mayor and up to three ballots for separate councillors with a voter's designated ward.\n\nKey issues in the election were expansion of the sewer system, public health related to the spread of scarlet fever, municipally owned electric light systems, prohibition, and expanded fire protection.<ref name=\"CGYHLDDec08Pg04\">{{cite news |title=Parish Politics Talked |url=http://contentdm.ucalgary.ca/digital/collection/p22007coll2/id/101377 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=The Daily Herald |issue=5550 |date=December 8, 1902 |location=Calgary, Canada |page=4}}</ref>\n\n==Results==\n===Mayor===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Candidate\n! Votes\n! Percent\n|-\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | [[Thomas Underwood]]\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | 419\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | 60.81%\n|-\n| [[William Mahon Parslow]]\n| style=\"text-align: right; \"| 270\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 39.19%\n|-\n! Total\n! style=\"text-align: right; \"|419\n! style=\"text-align: right; \"|-\n|}\n\n===Councillors===\n====Ward 1====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Candidate\n! Votes\n! Percent\n|-\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | [[John Emerson (mayor)|John Emerson]]\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | 183\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | \n|-\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | [[Silas Alexander Ramsay]]\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | 182\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | \n|-\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | [[Owen Herbert Bott]]\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | 174\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | \n|-\n| Mackenzie\n| style=\"text-align: right; \" | 154\n| style=\"text-align: right; \" | \n|-\n| Pitman\n| style=\"text-align: right; \" | 85\n| style=\"text-align: right; \" | \n|}\n\n====Ward 2====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Candidate\n! Votes\n! Percent\n|-\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | [[John Irwin]]\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | 185\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | \n|-\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | [[William Carson (Alberta politician)|William Carson]]\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | 143\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | \n|-\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | [[William John Binning]]\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | 95\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | \n|-\n| [[John Hamilton Kerr]]\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 80\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | \n|-\n| Brown\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 61\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | \n|}\n\n====Ward 3====\n*[[William Charles Gordon Armstrong]] - Acclaimed\n*[[Richard Addison Brocklebank]] - Acclaimed\n*[[James Abel Hornby]] - Acclaimed\n===School Trustees===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Candidate\n! Votes\n! Percent\n|-\n| R. F. Hutchings\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 408\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | \n|-\n| A. L. Cameron\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 364\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | \n|-\n| Clifford Jones\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 333\n| style=\"text-align: right; font-weight:bold;\" | \n|-\n|}\n\n==September 1902 by-election==\nFollowing [[William Carson (Alberta politician)|William Carson's]] decision to decline the office of Alderman for Ward 2 communicated to the City Clerk on December 18, 1902, a by-election was held which was won by [[William Henry Cushing]].\n\n==Also See==\n*[[List of Calgary municipal elections]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|1}}\n\n==Sources==\n*Frederick Hunter: [http://freepages.rootsweb.com/~database/history/THE%20MAYORS%20AND%20COUNCILS%20OF%20THE%20CORPORATION%20OF%20CALGARY.htm THE MAYORS AND COUNCILS  OF  THE CORPORATION OF CALGARY] [https://web.archive.org/web/20200303003535/http://freepages.rootsweb.com/~database/history/THE%20MAYORS%20AND%20COUNCILS%20OF%20THE%20CORPORATION%20OF%20CALGARY.htm Archived March 3, 2020]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Calgary Municipal Election, 1902}}\n[[Category:Politics of Calgary]]\n[[Category:Municipal elections in Calgary]]\n[[Category:1902 elections in Canada]]\n[[Category:1900s in Calgary]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toJohn Irwin(link changed toJohn Irwin (politician)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1902_Calgary_municipal_election"}
{"title_page": "Netumbo Nandi-Ndaitwah", "text_new": "{{Infobox Officeholder\n|honorific-prefix    = Honourable\n|name                = Netumbo Nandi-Ndaitwah\n|honorific-suffix    = MP\n|image               = Netumbo Nandi-Ndaitwah(cropped).jpg\n|imagesize           = \n|smallimage          =\n|caption             = \n|order               = \n|office         = [[Prime Minister of Namibia|Deputy Prime Minister of Namibia]]\n|primeminister  = [[Saara Kuugongelwa]]\n|term_start     = 21 March 2015\n|term_end       = \n|predecessor    = [[Marco Hausiku]]\n|successor      =\n\n|office2         = [[List of Ministers of Foreign Affairs (Namibia)|Minister of International Relations and Cooperation]]\n|primeminister2  = [[Hage Geingob]]<br>[[Saara Kuugongelwa]]\n|term_start2     = 4 December 2012\n|term_end2       = \n|predecessor2    = [[Utoni Nujoma]]\n|successor2      =\n\n|office3        = Minister of Environment and Tourism\n|primeminister3 = [[Nahas Angula]]\n|term_start3    = 21 March 2010\n|term_end3      = 4 December 2012\n|predecessor3   = [[Willem Konjore]]\n|successor3     = [[Uahekua Herunga]]\n\n\n|office4        = Minister of Information and Technology \n|primeminister4 = [[Nahas Angula]]\n|term_start4    = 2005\n|term_end4      = 2010\n|predecessor4   =\n|successor4     =\n\n|office5       = Minister of Women Affairs and Child Welfare\n|primeminister5 = [[Hage Geingob]]\n|term_start5   = 2000\n|term_end5     = 2005\n|predecessor5  =\n|successor5    = \n\n|office6      = Director General of Women Affairs \n|primeminister6 = [[Hage Geingob]]\n|term_start6   = 1996\n|term_end6     = 2000\n|predecessor6  =\n|successor6     = \n\n|office7        = Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs\n|primeminister7 = [[Hage Geingob]]\n|term_start7   = 21 March 1990 \n|term_end7      = 21 March 1996\n|predecessor7   = \n|successor7    =\n\n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1952|10|29}}\n|birth_place    = [[Oshana Region|Onamutai]], [[South West Africa]] {{small|(now [[Namibia]])}}\n|death_date     = \n|death_place    = \n|nationality         = {{flagicon|Namibia}} [[Namibia]]n\n|party               = [[Image:Flag of South West Africa People's Organisation.svg|24px]] [[South West Africa People's Organization|SWAPO]] \n|spouse         = [[Epaphras Denga Ndaitwah]]\n|alma_mater     = [[Keele University]]<br>[[Glasgow Caledonian University]]\n}}\n\n'''Netumbo Nandi-Ndaitwah''' (born 29 October 1952) is a [[Namibia]]n politician who is the [[Prime Minister of Namibia|Deputy Prime Minister of Namibia]] since March 2015. She has also been serving as Namibia's Minister of International Relations and Cooperation since December 2012. From March 2010 to December 2012, she was Minister of the Environment and [[Tourism in Namibia|Tourism]].  Nandi-Ndaitwah is a member of [[SWAPO]], Namibia's ruling party, and a long-time member of the [[National Assembly of Namibia]]. In 2017 Nandi-Ndaitwah was elected Vice-President of the [[SWAPO|Swapo Party]] at the party's 6th Congress. She is the first woman to serve in that position.\n\n==Political career==\nBorn at [[Onamutai]] in [[Oshana Region]], Nandi-Ndaitwah went into exile and joined SWAPO members in Zambia in 1974, worked at the [[SWAPO]] headquarters in [[Lusaka]]/[[Zambia]] from 1974 to 1975 and attended a course at the High Komsomol School in the [[Soviet Union]] from 1975 to 1976. She became the SWAPO Deputy Representative in Zambia from 1976 until 1978 and the Chief Representative in Zambia from 1978 to 1980. From 1980 until 1986 she was the SWAPO Chief Representative in East Africa, based at Dar es Salaam. She was a Member of the SWAPO Central Committee from 1976 to 1986 and President of the Namibian [[National Women's Organisation]] (NANAWO) from 1991 to 1994. She has been a Member of the [[National Assembly of Namibia]] since 1990. She was Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs from 1990 to 1996, Director-General for Women's Affairs in the Office of the President from 1996 to 2000 and subsequently Minister for Women's Affairs.\n\nNandi-Ndaitwah first gained ministerial status as Director-General of Women Affairs in the Office of the President in 1996. In 2000 she became Minister of Women Affairs and Child Welfare. She is a member of the Swapo Party Central Committee and Politburo and serves as Swapo's Secretary for Information and Mobilisation. As such Nandi-Ndaitwah is one of the party\u2019s main spokespersons.<ref name=NID>{{cite web\n |last        = Hopwood\n |first       = Graham\n |title       = Who's Who, entry for Netumbo Nandi-Ndaitwah\n |publisher   = Namibia Institute for Democracy\n |url         = http://www.nid.org.na/view_book_entry.php?book_id=128\n |accessdate  = 8 January 2014\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110611174934/http://www.nid.org.na/view_book_entry.php?book_id=128\n |archivedate = 11 June 2011\n}}</ref> From 2005 to 2010, she was the Minister of Information and Technology in [[Cabinet of Namibia (2005-10)|Namibia's cabinet]]. She subsequently served as Minister of Environment and Tourism until a major [[Cabinet of Namibia|Cabinet]] reshuffle in December 2012, in which she was appointed  Minister of Foreign Affairs.<ref name=\"reshuffle\">{{cite news\n|url=http://www.namibian.com.na/indexx.php?archive_id=103168&page_type=archive_story_detail&page=525\n|title=Transition team picked\n|last=Shipanga\n|first=Selma\n|last2=Immanuel\n|first2=Shinovene\n|date=5 December 2012\n|work=[[The Namibian]]\n|access-date=27 December 2013\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131228002035/http://www.namibian.com.na/indexx.php?archive_id=103168&page_type=archive_story_detail&page=525\n|archive-date=28 December 2013\n|url-status=dead\n}}</ref>\n\nUnder President [[Hage Geingob]], Nandi-Ndaitwah was appointed as Deputy Prime Minister in March 2015, while also serving as Minister of International Relations and Cooperation.<ref>[http://www.namibian.com.na/indexx.php?id=24638&page_type=story_detail \"Geingob announces Cabinet\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151002191233/http://www.namibian.com.na/indexx.php?id=24638&page_type=story_detail |date=2015-10-02 }}, ''The Namibian'', 20 March 2015.</ref>\n\n==Education==\n\nNdaitwah was educated at St. Mary's Mission in Odibo, obtained a master's degree in Diplomatic Studies<ref>http://www.klausdierks.com/Biographies/Biographies_N.htm</ref> from [[Keele University]], UK in (1989), she holds a post-graduate Diploma in [[International Relations]], Keele University, UK (1988), a post-graduate Diploma, Public Administration and Management, Glasgow College of Technology, UK (1987). Diploma in work and practice of communist youth movement, Lenin High Kosomol School, USSR (1976).\n\n==Personal life==\nNetumbo Nandi-Ndaitwah is married to [[Epaphras Denga Ndaitwah]], former Chief of the [[Namibian Defence Force]].<ref name=NID/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of foreign ministers in 2017]]\n*[[List of current foreign ministers]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nandi-Ndaitwah, Netumbo}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Deputy Prime Ministers of Namibia]]\n[[Category:Foreign Ministers of Namibia]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly (Namibia)]]\n[[Category:Members of SWAPO]]\n[[Category:People from Oshana Region]]\n[[Category:SWAPO politicians]]\n[[Category:Female foreign ministers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Keele University]]\n[[Category:21st-century women politicians]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of Namibia]]\n[[Category:Women members of the National Assembly (Namibia)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Officeholder\n|honorific-prefix    = Honourable\n|name                = Netumbo Nandi-Ndaitwah\n|honorific-suffix    = MP\n|image               = Netumbo Nandi-Ndaitwah(cropped).jpg\n|imagesize           = \n|smallimage          =\n|caption             = \n|order               = \n|office         = [[Prime Minister of Namibia|Deputy Prime Minister of Namibia]]\n|primeminister  = [[Saara Kuugongelwa]]\n|term_start     = 21 March 2015\n|term_end       = \n|predecessor    = [[Marco Hausiku]]\n|successor      =\n\n|office2         = [[List of Ministers of Foreign Affairs (Namibia)|Minister of International Relations and Cooperation]]\n|primeminister2  = [[Hage Geingob]]<br>[[Saara Kuugongelwa]]\n|term_start2     = 4 December 2012\n|term_end2       = \n|predecessor2    = [[Utoni Nujoma]]\n|successor2      =\n\n|office3        = Minister of Environment and Tourism\n|primeminister3 = [[Nahas Angula]]\n|term_start3    = 21 March 2010\n|term_end3      = 4 December 2012\n|predecessor3   = [[Willem Konjore]]\n|successor3     = [[Uahekua Herunga]]\n\n\n|office4        = Minister of Information and Technology \n|primeminister4 = [[Nahas Angula]]\n|term_start4    = 2005\n|term_end4      = 2010\n|predecessor4   =\n|successor4     =\n\n|office5       = Minister of Women Affairs and Child Welfare\n|primeminister5 = [[Hage Geingob]]\n|term_start5   = 2000\n|term_end5     = 2005\n|predecessor5  =\n|successor5    = \n\n|office6      = Director General of Women Affairs \n|primeminister6 = [[Hage Geingob]]\n|term_start6   = 1996\n|term_end6     = 2000\n|predecessor6  =\n|successor6     = \n\n|office7        = Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs\n|primeminister7 = [[Hage Geingob]]\n|term_start7   = 21 March 1990 \n|term_end7      = 21 March 1996\n|predecessor7   = \n|successor7    =\n\n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1952|10|29}}\n|birth_place    = [[Oshana Region|Onamutai]], [[South West Africa]] {{small|(now [[Namibia]])}}\n|death_date     = \n|death_place    = \n|nationality         = {{flagicon|Namibia}} [[Namibia]]n\n|party               = [[Image:Flag of South West Africa People's Organisation.svg|24px]] [[South West Africa People's Organization|SWAPO]] \n|spouse         = [[Epaphras Denga Ndaitwah]]\n|alma_mater     = [[Keele University]]<br>[[Glasgow Caledonian University]]\n}}\n\n'''Netumbo Nandi-Ndaitwah''' (born 29 October 1952) is a [[Namibia]]n politician who is the [[Prime Minister of Namibia|Deputy Prime Minister of Namibia]] since March 2015. She also serves as Namibia's Minister of International Relations and Cooperation ever since December 2012. From March 2010 to December 2012, she was Minister of the Environment and [[Tourism in Namibia|Tourism]].  Nandi-Ndaitwah is a member of [[SWAPO]], Namibia's ruling party, and a long-time member of the [[National Assembly of Namibia]]. In 2017 Nandi-Ndaitwah was elected Vice-President of the [[SWAPO|Swapo Party]] at the party's 6th Congress. She is the first woman to serve in that position.\n\n==Political career==\nBorn at [[Onamutai]] in [[Oshana Region]], Nandi-Ndaitwah went into exile and joined SWAPO members in Zambia in 1974, worked at the [[SWAPO]] headquarters in [[Lusaka]]/[[Zambia]] from 1974 to 1975 and attended a course at the High Komsomol School in the [[Soviet Union]] from 1975 to 1976. She became the SWAPO Deputy Representative in Zambia from 1976 until 1978 and the Chief Representative in Zambia from 1978 to 1980. From 1980 until 1986 she was the SWAPO Chief Representative in East Africa, based at Dar es Salaam. She was a Member of the SWAPO Central Committee from 1976 to 1986 and President of the Namibian [[National Women's Organisation]] (NANAWO) from 1991 to 1994. She has been a Member of the [[National Assembly of Namibia]] since 1990. She was Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs from 1990 to 1996, Director-General for Women's Affairs in the Office of the President from 1996 to 2000 and subsequently Minister for Women's Affairs.\n\nNandi-Ndaitwah first gained ministerial status as Director-General of Women Affairs in the Office of the President in 1996. In 2000 she became Minister of Women Affairs and Child Welfare. She is a member of the Swapo Party Central Committee and Politburo and serves as Swapo's Secretary for Information and Mobilisation. As such Nandi-Ndaitwah is one of the party\u2019s main spokespersons.<ref name=NID>{{cite web\n |last        = Hopwood\n |first       = Graham\n |title       = Who's Who, entry for Netumbo Nandi-Ndaitwah\n |publisher   = Namibia Institute for Democracy\n |url         = http://www.nid.org.na/view_book_entry.php?book_id=128\n |accessdate  = 8 January 2014\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110611174934/http://www.nid.org.na/view_book_entry.php?book_id=128\n |archivedate = 11 June 2011\n}}</ref> From 2005 to 2010, she was the Minister of Information and Technology in [[Cabinet of Namibia (2005-10)|Namibia's cabinet]]. She subsequently served as Minister of Environment and Tourism until a major [[Cabinet of Namibia|Cabinet]] reshuffle in December 2012, in which she was appointed  Minister of Foreign Affairs.<ref name=\"reshuffle\">{{cite news\n|url=http://www.namibian.com.na/indexx.php?archive_id=103168&page_type=archive_story_detail&page=525\n|title=Transition team picked\n|last=Shipanga\n|first=Selma\n|last2=Immanuel\n|first2=Shinovene\n|date=5 December 2012\n|work=[[The Namibian]]\n|access-date=27 December 2013\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131228002035/http://www.namibian.com.na/indexx.php?archive_id=103168&page_type=archive_story_detail&page=525\n|archive-date=28 December 2013\n|url-status=dead\n}}</ref>\n\nUnder President [[Hage Geingob]], Nandi-Ndaitwah was appointed as Deputy Prime Minister in March 2015, while also serving as Minister of International Relations and Cooperation.<ref>[http://www.namibian.com.na/indexx.php?id=24638&page_type=story_detail \"Geingob announces Cabinet\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151002191233/http://www.namibian.com.na/indexx.php?id=24638&page_type=story_detail |date=2015-10-02 }}, ''The Namibian'', 20 March 2015.</ref>\n\n==Education==\n\nNdaitwah was educated at St. Mary's Mission in Odibo, obtained a master's degree in Diplomatic Studies<ref>http://www.klausdierks.com/Biographies/Biographies_N.htm</ref> from [[Keele University]], UK in (1989), she holds a post-graduate Diploma in [[International Relations]], Keele University, UK (1988), a post-graduate Diploma, Public Administration and Management, Glasgow College of Technology, UK (1987). Diploma in work and practice of communist youth movement, Lenin High Kosomol School, USSR (1976).\n\n==Personal life==\nNetumbo Nandi-Ndaitwah is married to [[Epaphras Denga Ndaitwah]], former Chief of the [[Namibian Defence Force]].<ref name=NID/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of foreign ministers in 2017]]\n*[[List of current foreign ministers]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nandi-Ndaitwah, Netumbo}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Deputy Prime Ministers of Namibia]]\n[[Category:Foreign Ministers of Namibia]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly (Namibia)]]\n[[Category:Members of SWAPO]]\n[[Category:People from Oshana Region]]\n[[Category:SWAPO politicians]]\n[[Category:Female foreign ministers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Keele University]]\n[[Category:21st-century women politicians]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of Namibia]]\n[[Category:Women members of the National Assembly (Namibia)]]\n", "name_user": "Lihanhendrikse", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Netumbo_Nandi-Ndaitwah"}
